HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 719
By Bulso
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Lewis "Lew" H. Conner,
Jr., of Nashville.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Lewis "Lew" H. Conner, Jr., of Nashville; and
WHEREAS, a highly respected attorney, judge, and philanthropist, Lew Conner was an
exemplary public servant and consummate professional who worked assiduously to improve the
quality of life for his fellow citizens in numerous capacities; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Conner was a native of Chattanooga and a proud graduate of
Vanderbilt University, where he earned his Bachelor of Arts degree in 1960 and his Juris Doctor
degree in 1963; during his collegiate career, he served as president of Alpha Tau Omega and
competed on the Men's Varsity Golf Team from 1957 to 1960; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Conner's commitment to Vanderbilt deepened over the years, and in
2017, he was inducted into the Vanderbilt Sports Hall of Fame, an honor that reflected not only
his role as an athlete but also his contributions as an innovator and visionary benefactor; and
WHEREAS, Lew Conner was instrumental in elevating Vanderbilt Golf to national
prominence, and his legacy is physically etched on campus through the Conner Family Hitting
Bays and the Conner Short Game Practice Facility at the Vanderbilt Legends Club, a state-of-
the-art practice facility that ensures generations of Commodores have the tools to excel; and
WHEREAS, often referred to as a "statesman of the game," Mr. Conner was the founder
and first amateur president of the Tennessee Golf Foundation, in which he served as the
primary architect of the Golf House Tennessee concept, an endeavor that ultimately unified the
Tennessee Golf Association and the Tennessee Section of the PGA; additionally, he served the
HJR0719
010896
- 1 -

organization as chairman and was a longtime director and president of the Tennessee Golf
Association; and
WHEREAS, an elite competitor, Lew Conner won thirty-five amateur tournaments and
secured both the 1973 Tennessee Amateur Player of the Year title and the inaugural
Tennessee Golfers' Person of the Year award in 2002; in 1996, he competed in both the USGA
Senior Amateur and Senior Open Championships, and in 2010, he was inducted into the
Tennessee Golf Hall of Fame; and
WHEREAS, following his service as a Captain in the Judge Advocate General's Corps
with the 101st Airborne Division (1963-1966), Mr. Conner entered private practice and went on
to cofound Dearborn & Ewing with partners who remained lifelong friends; as his private
practice career unfolded, his work in complex litigation led him to pioneer Alternative Dispute
Resolution in Tennessee; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Conner was widely regarded as one of the "fathers of mediation," and
his legal career was marked by a steadfast commitment to integrity and service and an
extraordinary record of successful resolutions; and
WHEREAS, Lew Conner was a recipient of the John C. Tune Public Service Award, the
highest distinction from the Nashville Bar Association, and the Best of the Bar Lifetime
Achievement Award; and
WHEREAS, a leader in his profession, Lew Conner served on the Tennessee Court of
Appeals with distinction from 1980 to 1984, and he later served as special chief justice of the
Tennessee Supreme Court; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Conner was a trusted advisor and strategist, having served as a finance
co-chair and counsel to many of Tennessee's most prominent leaders, including Lamar
Alexander, Fred Thompson, Bill Frist, Don Sundquist, Bill Haslam, and Bill Hagerty, and
mentored countless others in public service; and
- 2 - 010896

WHEREAS, Mr. Conner held leadership roles within the Boys & Girls Clubs, the
Nashville Sports Council, the Music City Bowl, and the National Commodore Club, and he was
a devoted member of Westminster Presbyterian Church; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Conner was also deeply devoted to his family, and he always
endeavored to remain true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, left to cherish his memory are his college sweetheart and beloved wife of
sixty-five years, Ashley Whitsitt Conner; his children, Holland (Holly) Conner Boyer and Lewis
Forrest Conner; his children's spouses, David Boyer and Stephanie Barger Conner; and his
grandchildren, Forrest Walker Conner, Elizabeth Lewis Conner, Virginia Ashley Conner, Luke
Coleman Boyer, and Martha Ashley Boyer; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Conner was preceded in death by his parents, Lewis H. Conner and
Cleo Johnson Conner, and his grandson, John Carlisle Conner; and
WHEREAS, Lew Conner leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Lewis "Lew" H. Conner, Jr., reflecting fondly upon
his impeccable character, his extraordinary contributions to the people of Tennessee, and his
stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Conner.
- 3 - 010896

BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
